[The above posts report increasing cases in children of invasive Group A streptococcal infection (iGAS) in the USA that have proved fatal in 2 children in the state of Colorado. However, we have not been told the specific types of iGAS that are occurring. _Streptococcus pyogenes_ is known to cause secondary bacterial pneumonia after viral respiratory tract infections, such as influenza, or secondary bacterial skin and soft tissue infections after chicken pox. Group A streptococcal infection can also be complicated by potentially fatal toxic shock syndrome, necrotizing fasciitis, bacteremia, endocarditis, and meningitis. Serious non-suppurative sequelae, such as acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease, and glomerulonephritis may also occur after GAS pharyngitis.

More information would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources as it becomes available. - Mod.ML

